    Flexible Porous Zinc–Pyrazole–Adenine Framework for Hysteretic Sorption of Light Hydrocarbons

    Abstract

    One porous metal–organic framework based on mixed ligands, [Zn5(4-pca)4(ade)2(H2O)2]·(DMF)·4(H2O) (1; 4-H2pca = 4-pyrazolecarboxylic acid, Hade = adenine, DMF = N,N-dimenthylformamide), has been synthesized solvothermally and structurally characterized. Interestingly, the framework of 1 shows reversible flexibility, so that the adsorption behaviors of this activated sample exhibit the gate-opening effect in response to light hydrocarbons (C2H2, C2H4, C2H6, and C3H8). As a result, it could serve as an excellent platform for storage and purification of small hydrocarbons.

    Synopsis

    A flexible porous framework based on a mixed 4-pyrazolecarboxylic acid−adenine system was synthesized and exhibits gate-opening adsorption in response to light hydrocarbons with high uptake capacity.

    Introduction

    ARTICLE SECTIONS

    • References
    Metal–organic frameworks (MOFs) combining the properties of high surface areas and porosity, tunable microenvironment of the framework, and predesigned architecture, show great potential applications in gas storage and separation.(1-3) As a subclass of metal–organic frameworks, flexible metal–organic frameworks (FMOFs) often show distinctive multistep or hysteretic gas sorption behaviors with reversible structural transformation during the sorption process.(4-6) These flexible porous frameworks have been regarded as a superior platform for gas capture and purification, especially for light hydrocarbons.(7-9)
    In the terms of design of FMOFs, pyrazolate-based ligands have been proven to be valid participants for the construction of flexible frameworks.(10, 11) Two nitrogen atoms of the pyrazolate ligand can provide the bridging mode to connect two metal ions. The bridging nitrogen atoms of the pyrazolate rings act as a “kneecap” around the M···M axis, which commonly leads to the rotation of ligands around the M···M axis in response to external stimulus and then gives rise to the deformation of the framework structure. Moreover, due to the high pKa of pyrazole, pyrazolato-containing spacers can form much stronger M–N bonds, leading to a framework with good chemical and thermal stability.(12, 13) Additionally, adenine with multiple Lewis-basic sites has been established as an ideal rigid linker for the construction of porous metal–organic frameworks.(14, 15) Meanwhile, adenine would adopt a similar bridging mode to pyrazole.(16, 17)
    In this work, mixed 4-pyrazolecarboxylate (4-pca) and adenine (ade) ligands are used to build a dynamic framework structure, and one new microporous MOF, [Zn5(4-pca)4(ade)2(H2O)2]·(DMF)·4(H2O) (1), is synthesized solvothermally and structurally characterized. The activated framework of 1 exhibits hysteretic sorption behaviors with high capacity for light hydrocarbons.

    Materials and Methods

    All solvents and starting materials for synthesis were purchased commercially and used without further purification. Thermogravimetric analyses (TGA), using NETSCHZ STA-449C equipment, were performed with a heating rate of 5 °C min–1. The product phase purity was examined by X-ray powder diffraction (PXRD), using a MiniFlex-II powder diffractometer (Cu Kα, 1.5418 Å). The gas sorption studies were measured with Micromeritics ASAP 2020 adsorption equipment.

    Synthesis of Compound 1

    A mixture of Zn(NO3)2·6H2O (48.0 mg, 0.160 mmol), 4-H2pca (14.0 mg, 0.120 mmol), and Hade (13.0 mg, 0.100 mmol) was dissolved in DMF/H2O (10 mL, 9:1, v/v) in a screw-capped vial and heated to 120 °C for 14 days. The resulting block shaped single crystals were washed with DMF several times. Elemental analysis Calcd For Zn5C35N21H47O16: C, 31.25; H, 3.50; N, 18.75. Found: C, 30.11; H, 3.88; N: 17.12.

    X-ray Diffraction Analysis

    The single crystal X-ray diffraction measurements were performed on an XCalibur E CCD diffractometer equipped with a graphite monochromated Mo Kα radiation (λ = 0.71073 Å) at 293(2) K. The structure was solved by direct methods and refined on F2 full-matrix least-squares using the SHELXTL-97(18) program package. All non-hydrogen atoms were refined with anisotropic parameters. All the hydrogen atoms were generated geometrically. The SQUEEZE option of PLATON was used to eliminate the contribution of disordered guest molecules to the reflection intensities. Crystallographic data of 1 is given in Table 1.

    Results and Discussion

    ARTICLE SECTIONS
    Jump To
    • Abstract
    • Introduction
    • Materials and Methods
    • Results and Discussion
    • Conclusion
    • Supporting Information
    • Acknowledgment
    • References
    Compound 1 features a three-dimensional open framework with intrinsically chiral quartz topology. Single crystal X-ray structure analysis shows that 1 crystallizes in the chiral space group of P21212. The asymmetric unit of 1 consists of three independent Zn ions, two 4-pca ligands, one μ3-ade ligands, and one coordinated water molecule (Figure 1a). Two 4-pca ligands adopt one kind of coordination mode: two pyrazole nitrogen atoms bridge two Zn(II) ions and one carboxylate oxygen atom connects one Zn(II) ion. The μ3-ade ligand links three independent Zn ions, and two Zn ions (Zn1 and Zn2) are bridged together by one μ3-ade ligand and two 4-pca ligands to form a dinuclear unit with Zn···Zn distance of 3.3338(15) Å. All independent Zn ions adopt tetrahedral coordination geometry. The dinuclear unit is surrounded by one μ3-ade ligand, one aqua molecule, and three 4-pca ligands, while the simple Zn3 center is bonded by two nitrogen atoms from two ade ligands and two oxygen atoms from two 4-pca ligands. The dinuclear units and the Zn3 centers are further connected to other neighboring units to construct a 3D open framework (Figure 1b). Here, both the binuclear unit and Zn3 center act as 4-connected nodes, so the final framework of 1 can be topologically represented as a qtz net (Figure 1c). Since qtz net is intrinsically chiral, the chirality presented in this framework is obvious.(19, 20) The framework of 1 contains right-handed helices along the b-axis, giving rise to the left-handed channel (Figures 1b,d); the opening size of the window is ∼5.2 Å × 6.7 Å, which is explored by the Poreblazer V 3.1.2 program.(21) The void volume of 1 is 53.3% of the crystal volume (1972.3 out of the 3700.4 Å3 unit cell volume), calculated by PLATON (probe radius = 1.80 Å).(22)
    Thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) of 1 was carried out under N2 atmosphere (Figure S1 in the Supporting Information), revealing that compound 1 can be stable up to 320 °C. A fresh sample of 1 was dipped in methanol, the solution was exchanged ten times in 3 days, and then TGA of the activated sample was also performed. Activated compound 1 has weight loss of about 27% from 30 to 250 °C, indicating that the guests can be removed from the framework. Variable-temperature powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) measurement for 1 was performed from room temperature to 240 °C under an air atmosphere (Figure 2 and Figure S2, Supporting Information). The peaks of dehydrated compound 1 shows obvious shifting from low angles to high angles (9.94°, 11.27°, and 22.25° oriented toward to 10.38°, 11.98°, and 23.93°, respectively), confirming the flexibility and shrinkage of the framework. Moreover, the energy of the structure without guest molecules was minimized by Materials Studio/Forcite. The peak positions of the computational model from 10.19° shift slightly toward high angle compared with the peaks of the original sample. This result also proves that the framework has a degree of flexibility (Figure S4, Supporting Information). Additionally, the PXRD patterns could return back the original one, when the activated 1 was immersed in DMF solvent again (Figure S3 in the Supporting Information). The results show that the contraction–opening of the framework is reversible.
    The flexible features of the porous framework as well as free amino groups presented in the pores prompted us to investigate the gas sorption properties of 1. The permanent porosity of the desolvated form of 1 was established by N2 sorption experiments at 77 K, which showed type-I adsorption isotherm behavior (Figure S5 in the Supporting Information). The Langmuir and BET surface areas were 526.8 and 368.7 m2 g–1, respectively.
    The adsorption of the C1 to C3 light hydrocarbons was performed at 273 K and room temperature. The gas sorption isotherms of 1 are shown in Figure 3. Generally, the adsorption capacity of CH4 is relatively low, due to the weak interaction between methane and framework. The uptake values of other small hydrocarbons follow the trend C2H2 > C2H4 > C2H6 ≈ C3H8, which is in line with the increasing of kinetic diameter of the gases. Moreover, large hysteretic behaviors can be observed. Compound 1 can take up 134.0 cm3 g –1 C2H2, and a moderate amount of C2H4 (90.0 cm3 g–1), C2H6 (84.3 cm3 g–1), and C3H8 (80 cm3 g–1) at 273 K and 1 bar and C2H2 (109.9 cm3 g–1), C2H4 (79.3 cm3 g–1), C2H6 (69.3 cm3 g–1), and C3H8 (73.4 cm3 g–1) at 290 K and 1 bar.
    Specially, for the dynamic adsorption of compound 1 at 273 K, the adsorption branch of C2H2 shows a slight slope on the whole. The desorption pathway cannot trace the adsorption curve, resulting in a hysteretic behavior. Different from C2H2, the isotherms of C2H4 and C2H6 show distinct hysteretic loops. The opening pressure from narrow pore to big pore need 610 and 550 mmHg for C2H4 and C2H6, then the C2H4 and C2H6 adsorption abruptly increase, and the door-closing pressure is nearly up to 760 mmHg for C2H4 and C2H6. Moreover, the desorption branches only have slight decrease until 89 and 101 mmHg, generating very large hysteretic loops. These results indicate that such compound could serve as the candidate for ethylene and ethane storage via a kinetics-based trapping process. For C3H8, the first stage reaches the inflection point at a very low pressure of 29 mmHg, and the uptake is close to saturation at 110 mmHg. Obviously, the transformation pressure between narrow pore and large pore of C3H8 becomes lower than that of C2H4 and C2H6.
    Similar to the sorption results at 273 K, hysteretic sorption behaviors of compound 1 were observed at 290 K (Figure 3b). However, the opening pressures shift to higher values and the width of the loops become larger. Because a certain amount of probe gas is needed for expansion of framework, higher pressure is needed to overcome the obstacles of diffusion of gas molecules at higher temperature.
    It is worth mentioning that the uptake values of light hydrocarbons in 1 are higher than those of ZJU-48a,(23) UTSA-38a,(24) and MCOF-1,(25) although the pore volume of 1 is small. This can be attributed to the proper window size and the decorated amino groups in 1. Compound 1 is a microporous framework with ∼0.75 nm pore size, which may be suitable for light hydrocarbons (kinetic diameters between 0.2–0.6 nm).(26, 27) On the other hand, upon activation, the Zn2 center will have an opening coordination site due to the removal of the coordinated water (O1w). Moreover, the acetylene has a smaller kinetic diameter (3.3 Å) compared with C2H4 (4.2 Å) and C2H6 (4.4 Å). With increasing adsorption strength of π-complexation adsorbents between the unsaturated Zn2 centers and the unsaturated hydrocarbons, compound 1 takes up the higher capacity of C2H2 over C2H4 and C2H6. Additionally, the gate-opening pressures are lower for acetylene and ethane than that for ethylene, a similar effect was observed by Gascon et al. in the framework ZIF-7 with a similar pore size (7.5 Å), which shows stepwise isotherms of C2–C3 light hydrocarbon isomers.(28) The structural transitions can be attribute to the consequence of adsorbate–adsorbent interactions. Noncovalent interactions, such as H-bonding, CH···π interactions or van der Waals interactions, between a dsorbents and the MOF matrix play an important role in the adsorption of light hydrocarbons. Moreover, the gate opening and large hysteresis can be explained like a similar structure Cu(btd).(29, 30) The rotation of coordination bonds formed by binuclear zinc and coordination nitrogen atoms causes the structural transitions upon response to light hydrocarbons in the sorption process.

    Conclusion

    ARTICLE SECTIONS
    Jump To

    • Introduction
    • Materials and Methods
    • Results and Discussion
    • Conclusion
    • Supporting Information
    • Acknowledgment
    • References
    In summary, one flexible MOF based on mixed 4-pyrazolecarboxylate and adenine ligands has been successfully synthesized. As expected, this compound exhibits the gate-opening and hysteretic adsorption behaviors in response to light hydrocarbons with high capacity. The results reveal that MOFs with kinetics-based sorption process may be good for storage and purification of light hydrocarbons.

      This crit. review highlights supermol. building blocks (SBBs) in the context of their impact upon the design, synthesis, and structure of metal-org. materials (MOMs). MOMs, also known as coordination polymers, hybrid inorg.-org. materials, and metal-org. frameworks, represent an emerging class of materials that have attracted the imagination of solid-state chemists because MOMs combine unprecedented levels of porosity with a range of other functional properties that occur through the metal moiety and/or the org. ligand. First generation MOMs exploited the geometry of metal ions or secondary building units (SBUs), small metal clusters that mimic polygons, for the generation of MOMs. In this crit. review we examine the recent (<5 years) adoption of much larger scale metal-org. polyhedra (MOPs) as SBBs for the construction of MOMs by highlighting how the large size and high symmetry of such SBBs can afford improved control over the topol. of the resulting MOM and a new level of scale to the resulting framework (204 refs.).

      Furukawa, Shuhei; Reboul, Julien; Diring, Stephane; Sumida, Kenji; Kitagawa, Susumu
      Chemical Society Reviews (2014), 43 (16), 5700-5734CODEN: CSRVBR; ISSN:0306-0012. (Royal Society of Chemistry)
      A review. The assembly of metal ions with org. ligands through the formation of coordination bonds gives cryst. framework materials, known as metal-org. frameworks (MOFs), which recently emerged as a new class of porous materials. Besides the structural designability of MOFs at the mol. length scale, the researchers in this field very recently made important advances in creating more complex architectures at the mesoscopic/macroscopic scale, in which MOF nanocrystals were used as building units to construct higher-order superstructures. The structuring of MOFs in such a hierarchical order certainly opens a new opportunity to improve the material performance via design of the phys. form rather than altering the chem. component. This review highlights these superstructures and their applications by categorizing them into four dimensionalities, zero-dimensional (0D), 1-dimensional (1D), two-dimensional (2D), and three-dimensional (3D) superstructures. Because the key issue for structuring of MOFs is to spatially control the nucleation process in desired locations, this review conceptually categorizes the available synthetic methodologies from the viewpoint of the reaction system.

      On the Flexibility of Metal-Organic Frameworks
      Sarkisov, Lev; Martin, Richard L.; Haranczyk, Maciej; Smit, Berend
      Journal of the American Chemical Society (2014), 136 (6), 2228-2231CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
      Occasional, large amplitude flexibility in metal-org. frameworks (MOFs) is one of the most intriguing recent discoveries in chem. and material science. Yet, there is at present no theor. framework that permits the identification of flexible structures in the rapidly expanding universe of MOFs. Here, we propose a simple method to predict whether a MOF is flexible, based on treating it as a system of rigid elements, connected by hinges. This proposition is correct in application to MOFs based on rigid carboxylate linkers. We validate the method by correctly classifying known exptl. MOFs into rigid and flexible groups. Applied to hypothetical MOFs, the method reveals an abundance of flexibility phenomena, and this seems to be at odds with the proportion of flexible structures among exptl. known MOFs. We speculate that the flexibility of a MOF may constitute an intrinsic impediment on its exptl. realization. This highlights the importance of systematic prediction of large amplitude flexibility regimes in MOFs.

      A review. Much attention has recently been focused on soft porous crystals, a fascinating subclass of metal-org. frameworks that behave in a remarkable stimuli-responsive fashion, presenting structural changes of large amplitude in response to guest adsorption, mech. pressure, or variations in temp. In this Perspective, the authors summarize the recently developed thermodn. and mech. theor. models for the understanding of these materials, based on the concepts of adsorption stress and osmotic thermodn. ensemble. The authors show how these models provide a coherent picture of adsorption-induced deformation and structural transitions in flexible metal-org. frameworks, all the way from the length scale of the unit cell to that of the full crystal. The authors highlight the new perspectives opened by these models, as well as some of the important open questions in the field.

      Schneemann, A.; Bon, V.; Schwedler, I.; Senkovska, I.; Kaskel, S.; Fischer, R. A.
      Chemical Society Reviews (2014), 43 (16), 6062-6096CODEN: CSRVBR; ISSN:0306-0012. (Royal Society of Chemistry)
      A review. Advances in flexible and functional metal-org. frameworks (MOFs), also called soft porous crystals, are reviewed by covering the literature of the five years period 2009-2013 with ref. to the early pertinent work since the late 1990s. Flexible MOFs combine the cryst. order of the underlying coordination network with cooperative structural transformability. These materials can respond to phys. and chem. stimuli of various kinds in a tunable fashion by mol. design, which does not exist for other known solid-state materials. Among the fascinating properties are so-called breathing and swelling phenomena as a function of host-guest interactions. Phase transitions are triggered by guest adsorption/desorption, photochem., thermal, and mech. stimuli. Other important flexible properties of MOFs, such as linker rotation and sub-net sliding, which are not necessarily accompanied by crystallog. phase transitions, are briefly mentioned as well. Emphasis is given on reviewing the recent progress in application of in situ characterization techniques and the results of theor. approaches to characterize and understand the breathing mechanisms and phase transitions. The flexible MOF systems, which are discussed, are categorized by the type of metal-nodes involved and how their coordination chem. with the linker mols. controls the framework dynamics. Aspects of tailoring the flexible and responsive properties by the mixed component solid-soln. concept are included, and as well examples of possible applications of flexible metal-org. frameworks for sepn., catalysis, sensing, and biomedicine.

      Ethane/ethene separation turned on its head: selective ethane adsorption on the metal-organic framework ZIF-7 through a gate-opening mechanism
      Gucuyener Canan; van den Bergh Johan; Gascon Jorge; Kapteijn Freek
      Journal of the American Chemical Society (2010), 132 (50), 17704-6 ISSN:.
      Ethane is selectively adsorbed over ethylene in their mixtures on the zeolite imidazolate framework ZIF-7. In packed columns, this results in the direct production of pure ethylene. This gas-phase separation is attributed to a gate-opening effect in which specific threshold pressures control the uptake and release of individual molecules. This phenomenon makes ZIF-7 a perfect candidate for the separation of olefins from paraffins, since in contrast to most microporous materials, the paraffin is selectively adsorbed.         A review. The assembly of metal ions with org. ligands through the formation of coordination bonds gives cryst. framework materials, known as metal-org. frameworks (MOFs), which recently emerged as a new class of porous materials. Besides the structural designability of MOFs at the mol. length scale, the researchers in this field very recently made important advances in creating more complex architectures at the mesoscopic/macroscopic scale, in which MOF nanocrystals were used as building units to construct higher-order superstructures.         On the Flexibility of Metal-Organic Frameworks
        Sarkisov, Lev; Martin, Richard L.; Haranczyk, Maciej; Smit, Berend
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2014), 136 (6), 2228-2231CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        Occasional, large amplitude flexibility in metal-org. frameworks (MOFs) is one of the most intriguing recent discoveries in chem. and material science. Yet, there is at present no theor. framework that permits the identification of flexible structures in the rapidly expanding universe of MOFs. Here, we propose a simple method to predict whether a MOF is flexible, based on treating it as a system of rigid elements, connected by hinges. This proposition is correct in application to MOFs based on rigid carboxylate linkers. We validate the method by correctly classifying known exptl. MOFs into rigid and flexible groups. We speculate that the flexibility of a MOF may constitute an intrinsic impediment on its exptl. realization. This highlights the importance of systematic prediction of large amplitude flexibility regimes in MOFs.

        Ethane/ethene separation turned on its head: selective ethane adsorption on the metal-organic framework ZIF-7 through a gate-opening mechanism
        Gucuyener Canan; van den Bergh Johan; Gascon Jorge; Kapteijn Freek
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2010), 132 (50), 17704-6 ISSN:.
        Ethane is selectively adsorbed over ethylene in their mixtures on the zeolite imidazolate framework ZIF-7. In packed columns, this results in the direct production of pure ethylene.         van den Bergh, Johan; Guecueyener, Canan; Pidko, Evgeny A.; Hensen, Emiel J. M.; Gascon, Jorge; Kapteijn, Freek

        Microporous Metal-Organic Frameworks Incorporating 1,4-Benzeneditetrazolate: Syntheses, Structures, and Hydrogen Storage Properties
        Dinca, Mircea; Yu, Anta F.; Long, Jeffrey R.
        Journal of the American Chemical Society (2006), 128 (27), 8904-8913CODEN: JACSAT; ISSN:0002-7863. (American Chemical Society)
        The potential of tetrazolate-based ligands for forming metal-org. frameworks of utility in hydrogen storage is demonstrated using 1,4-benzeneditetrazolate (BDT2-) to generate robust, microporous materials. Reaction of H2BDT with MnCl2·4H2O and Mn(NO3)2·4H2O in N,N-diethylformamide (DEF) produces the two-dimensional framework solids Mn3(BDT)2Cl2(DEF)6 (1) and Mn4(BDT)3(NO3)2(DEF)6 (2), whereas reactions with hydrated salts of Mn2+, Cu2+, and Zn2+ in a mixt. of methanol and DMF afford the porous, three-dimensional framework solids Zn3(BDT)3(DMF)4(H2O)2·3.5CH3OH (3), Mn3(BDT)3(DMF)4(H2O)2·3CH3OH·2H2O·DMF (4), Mn2(BDT)Cl2(DMF)2·1.5CH3OH·H2O (5), and Cu(BDT)(DMF)·CH3OH·0.25DMF (6). The method for desolvating such compds. can dramatically influence the ensuing gas sorption properties. When subjected to a mild evacuation procedure, compds. 3-6 exhibit permanent porosity, with BET surface areas in the range 200-640 m2/g. The desolvated forms of 3-5 store between 0.82 and 1.46% H2 at 77 K and 1 atm, with enthalpies of adsorption in the range 6.0-8.8 kJ/mol, among the highest so far reported for metal-org. frameworks. The desolvated form of 6 exhibits preferential adsorption of O2 over H2 and N2, showing promise for gas sepn. and purifn. applications.

        Selective Gas Adsorption in the Flexible Metal-Organic Frameworks Cu(BDTri)L (L=DMF, DEF)
        Demessence, Aude; Long, Jeffrey R.
        Chemistry - A European Journal (2010), 16 (20), 5902-5908, S5902/1-S5902/7CODEN: CEUJED; ISSN:0947-6539. (Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA)
        Use of the ditopic ligand 1,4-benzenedi(1H-1,2,3-triazole) (H2BDTri) enabled isolation of two new three-dimensional metal-org. frameworks of formulas Cu(BDTri)L in which L=DMF (1) and diethylformamide (DEF; 2). These compds. have the same primary structure, featuring one-dimensional channels with the bridging DMF or DEF mols. pointing into the cavity. Upon exposure to solvent vapors, both display a reversible flexibility, as characterized by single-crystal to single-crystal phase transitions in 1. The O2 adsorption isotherms for the compds. show a two-step adsorption behavior assocd. with a permanent microporosity and a pore-opening process. In the case of N2 adsorption, only 1 exhibits a two-step adsorption isotherm, whereas 2 does not present any pore opening, demonstrating that design of a flexible framework cavity can control the pore opening and thereby possibly enhance O2/N2 sepn.
